Changes Finally Revealed
CURRICUlUM ALTERED TO FIT REPORT
By ADRlENNE LEMMONS
58x3 Staff Writer
After 5 e v er al months of
heated scrutiny, the faculty has
approved, with a few amendmerits, nearly all of the rec<
observations submitted last
fall by the Committee on Educational Policy and Curriculum.
The report included changes
in course requirements, independent study, and academic
credit for some activities now
considered extra-curriculum.
Course requirements, according to Joseph F. Wall (history),
Chairman of the Faculty, have
been altered along the lines
suggested in the curriculum re»
port. Beginning with 1968 incoming freshmen, students will
meet these requirements:
—communities I and II, freshman year.
This course will attempt,
like the present Humanities
course, to teach techniques of
texture interpretation; the new
syllabus Will provide more study
at drama as a literary genre
and will probably include some
recent Works.
—Social Studies I and Il,
This is to be completed be
more the end or the sophomore
year. Readings will cover
“classic texts in social thought,
including texts in philosophy,
religion, politics, economics, sociology and anthropology."
The first semester, cancer«
trading on periods ranging from
classical Greece to the investments century, will draw heavily on philosophy, while the sec<
and semester, covering periods
from the French Revolution to
the present, will stress the social sciences. Emphasis will be
on intensive study at the ideas
and social issues of a new selected periods rather than a
technological survey of history.
—science l and ii,
Which must be completed by
the end of the sophomore year.
The two courses will serve as
an introduction to biological
and physical sciences. Science
I is planned for the fall of
1968, with Science ll following
by spring ol 1969.
—Proﬁagency in a foreign
language equal to two years of
college study.
The present philosophy requirement will remain for students who have taken Historical Studies, but will not be
obligation for Social Studies students.
The fate of Humanities Ill, 1:
course in music or visual arts
anonymous to the present introduction to Music and. introduction to Art courses, is still
undefined. A proposed change
would eliminate Introduction
to Theater as a means of
meeting the fine arts requirement, since Humanities I and
[I are expected to device more
study to dramatic works.
To combat: a sentence toward overspecialization, an upperclass general education requirement has been approved.
Beginning with 1968.59 freshmen,
all students will be required
to take 16 hours either in a
special, nonrmajor program or
in elections outside the division
at the student's major, of which
at least two courses must be
Zoo-level or above.
Committees are being formed
to design special interdisciplinary programs to fulfil this requirement. Areas being considered include Religous Studies, Urban Studies, International Studies, Communication Studies, and Studies in Philosophy
and Science.
In addition, 4 Credits of independent study will be re
quoted (it all students beginning with the graduation class
of 1972. Besides the present
2. and 4-credit independence, a
plan for course-related study is
being entered, thereby a student in a 4-hour course can
elect to pursue a 2-hour project under the same teacher.
The 2- and 4-credit components
