item on i. o. Grinnell while doing research for
his corporate in the history oi education.)
In february, 1866, Grinncll, allen serving in his second
term in the House oi Representatives, gave a speech on
the floor vehemently accounting those Kentucky representatives who opposed the Freedmen's Bill, a proposal designed to protect Southern degrees from local violence and
discrimination.
A few months later, Representative Rousseau, one of
the Kentuckians against the bill, attacked Grinnell public—
ly in a New York speech, calling him a “variable politician
