By BARRY ANCONA
l have noted that touring companies performances at Grinhell have always produced an coordinate amount of applause. 1
think I know why. The country kids are glad to have any expo«
sure to culture, and the City kids, normally started out here, are
keen for any recorders of home.
This may seem a very Stucksup, better-than-thou attitude.
It is.
Wicked City is a touring company — a New York show on
the road. Maybe you got a climate oi it Visiting the big town, but
let me tell you: New York is a great place to live, but i worlds’t
want [0 Visit.
To really appreciate the wicked city e any wicked city —
you have to live in it; feel it in you as you try to find white you're
about.
When you grow up in a small town, as you get older, you
get to know more and more people in the town. When you grow
up in a city, as you get older you get to know more and more
people, but you also meet thousands of people you don’t know.
This is the challenging thing about life in the city 7 the people
you meet every day that you don’t know, that you will never
see again.
It’s trighteiiing when you are united, a block from your home,
by someone you have never seen before. It’s a relief to know you
may never see him again. it’s exciting to meet some girl you’ve
never seen before. And depression to think you may never see
her again.
But that's what Wicked City is all about. The high school
pass, and girls next door, and every smalHown way of life is
there, but it's spreading the make of interference and convenience,
the long sunday ride home, that makes the city unique.
I'm going to talk about a certain sunday line. i used it frequently during my senior year in high school. Mostly between
midnight and 3 am.
it would be nice to think that l was travelling long distances
to now my wild cats far from home, but it was just convenience
that almost every girl i knew lived in the West front, just off
the become Avenue line (That meant a 45 minute sunday ride
Ind a lo minute walk to get home),
Of course. these were Wicked City girls, They were my age
(15) or a bit younger. They did not go to my high school (it was
all boys). They were all bright. And pretty good-looking. And all
had some screen hang-up. i mean screen. Nothing ordinary in
hang-ups car them.
One girl had a mother who was trying to act the age that the
girl was, and correspondingly tried to make the girl look and act
like a live-learned. One girl had a Jewish father and a Catholic
mother who got disorder. The father then married a protecting.
The girl also wanted to be a ballet cancer. But her build (about
five feet tall, and lives proof that the cantilever principle works),
although quite appearing. was not cut out, so to speak, for ballet.
One girl had a great home life, and was happy in her work and
play, and could have passed for Nancy Normal, if she hadn't been
a bit hungary because she was rated when she was eleven.
My only hanging was that I was hung on girls with hangrups.
A real social worker. With a few interior notices
But back to that sunday. it would be possible, I imagine, to
have three such girls living on three blocks of Main Street, print
hell. But to come and go with each one without detection by the
others would require travelling through the fewer system and
posting out of included storm trains. That’s kind of what the
sunday is.
The become Avenue line is not a sunday at all in the front
— it is an operated. The station platforms bizrate as trains pass.
You can look down between the ties to the street below, or, over
your shoulder, into Somebody’s apartment. Most of the platform
is recovered — you can wait twenty minutes in a blizzard for
a train.
When you ride a sunday train at night, you ride in either the
first or the middle car. The motorola is in the first, and the
conducted in the middle. This was in the days before policemen
code the trains. I was five [eat four inches in those days.
it's different now. When i drive my car in the city, I feel I've
turned it. It's so safe and isolated in a car. But park the Car and
walk a block and the old feeling is back.
There is a challenge to walk a straight line, with unexpected
pleasure and pain looking right and left. And when you realize
that y’ou’must expect the unexpected, 'you have submitted to the ,
