DADA, ART AND ANTI-ART
By ROBIN STANDISH
LIBERATION News Service
Dada, Art and Anti-Art.
Hans fighter. lvlccraw i-iili.
53.95 paperback.
Dada represents an unfinished revolution in art, one
that our movement artists today are continuing. Dada was
a great era when art was an
organic part or the artist‘s
life; artists were not afraid to
make a statement, they wanted
to communicate on Vital levels, and art gave meaning to
their lives. Arr, llle. and revolution were united. The publication ol l-land fighter's magnificent book. Dada, Art and
Anti-Art is an important event,
for Dada raises some vital
questions not only about art,
but about life and revolution.
We who are Movement people, following the lead of the
anarchists and other recently—
lists and libertarians, are becoming more and more coitcerned to live our revolution.
We are seeking to build a life
which is registration before
(or at least at the same time
as) i! is revolutionary, a life
which creates the new, in our
own lives, while it desktops
the delay in society (and in
our own lives). Can this be
done? Or is a whole, registration life hypothetical to a
struggle for massive social
Change?
We all know what happened
in prerNazi Germany. The Dadaists did not prevent either,
and neither did deeply antiNazi people who withdrew from
the struggle both psychically
and physically to live begin»
ei'alive lives in rural infections
al communities such as the
Bruderhot. Yet both groups after us some clubs.
some people are seeking
rural communities which will
maintain Itmnz ties with the ‘
city, with a lot or movement
back and forth, as people work
in free universities, guerilla
theater, etc, Some will manage
to make their peace With the
city, finding registration lives
with or without community. For
some people, art offers its
own answer, Yea—saying Dada
was concerned with the reports
of society. Art of this nature
is revolutionary; it gets in
people’s gets. Art as the com—
medication of life, art as an
extension of self to others,—
art from community in the
form or guerilla theater, music,
painting, whatever—such art offers a synthesis of a registration lite and revolutionary social change. When this happens, we are picking up on the
unﬁlisted revolution of Dada.
Dada, Art and Anti-Art is a
loving account by one of Dada's
creature, hence its vitamins and
spirit. This is nu mere similarly history, though it processes
that element too. The book is
filled with pictures, some in
color. There is a good selection of drawings and posters,
and even some poetry and short
plays. in addition there are
pictures of the artists, and it
is a great delight to find that
Hans rrp looks like his work.
The $3.95 paperback is a version of a gorgeous s50 cards
back, an awesiuspiring book
that good public libraries should
have.
